This document contains basics of Hartree-Fock-Bogoliubov Theory.   
  H =  \sum_{ij} T_{ij} c_{i}^{\dagger} c_{j}
     + \frac{1}{4} \sum_{ijkl} V_{ijkl} c_{i}^{\dagger} c_{j}^{\dagger} c_{l} c_{k}    
\begin{aligned}
  \Gamma_{ij} &= \sum_{kl} V_{ikjl} \rho_{lk} \\
  \Gamma_{ik} &= \sum_{kl} V_{ijkl} \rho_{lj} \\
  \Delta_{ij} &= \frac{1}{2} \sum_{kl} V_{ijkl} t_{kl}
\end{aligned}

Let us first consider the  diagonal  interaction of the form   
  V c_{1}^{\dagger} c_{2}^{\dagger} c_{2} c_{1} ,   which is the Hermitian conjugate of itself. Following Goodman [?], this interaction decomposes into the following mean fields in the particle-hole and particle-particle channels:     Interaction  PH Channel  PP Channel      V(1212) =  V  Γ(11) =  V ρ(22)  Δ(12) =  ½ V t(12)    V(1221) = -V  Γ(12) = -V ρ(12)  Δ(12) = -½ V t(21)    V(2112) = -V  Γ(21) = -V ρ(21)  Δ(21) = -½ V t(12)    V(2121) =  V  Γ(22) =  V ρ(11)  Δ(21) =  ½ V t(21)     Here, the equal sign '=' does not indicate equality. Rather, it refers to the contribution of the right hand side to the mean field on the left hand side. Some of the mean fields are redundant, as required by the Hermiticity of the Hamiltonian. Overall, we end up with   
\begin{aligned}
\Gamma_{11} &=  V \rho_{22} \\
\Gamma_{12} &= -V \rho_{12} \\
\Gamma_{22} &=  V \rho_{11}
\end{aligned}   in the particle-hole channel, and    
\begin{aligned}
Δ_{12} =  V t_{12}
\end{aligned}   in the particle-particle channel.

